{
  "State Faraday's Law.": "",
  "EMF = BIL": "",
  "EMF = Φ/t": "",
  "EMF = IR": "",
  "EMF = −dΦ/dt": "",
  "Faraday's Law: EMF = −dΦ/dt. A changing magnetic flux induces an EMF.": "",
  "What is magnetic flux?": "",
  "Φ = BA cos θ": "",
  "Φ = BA²": "",
  "Φ = B/A": "",
  "Φ = BA sin θ": "",
  "Magnetic flux Φ = BA cos θ, where B is field strength, A is area, and θ is the angle between B and the area normal.": "",
  "State Lenz's Law.": "",
  "There is no induced current": "",
  "Induced current opposes the change in flux that caused it": "",
  "Current always flows clockwise": "",
  "Induced current aids the change in flux": "",
  "Lenz's Law: The induced current flows in a direction that opposes the change in flux that caused it. This ensures energy conservation.": "",
  "Does a constant magnetic flux induce an EMF?": "",
  "No — flux must be changing": "",
  "Yes": "",
  "Only in superconductors": "",
  "Only in coils": "",
  "Only a changing flux induces an EMF. Constant flux through a loop produces zero EMF.": "",
  "What does a generator convert?": "",
  "Mechanical energy to electrical energy": "",
  "Chemical to kinetic": "",
  "Heat to light": "",
  "Electrical to mechanical": "",
  "A generator converts mechanical energy to electrical energy via electromagnetic induction.": "",
  "Name two applications of electromagnetic induction.": "",
  "Batteries and resistors": "",
  "Magnets and compasses": "",
  "Generators and transformers": "",
  "Capacitors and inductors": "",
  "Generators and transformers are key applications of electromagnetic induction.": "",
  "Why is there a negative sign in Faraday's Law?": "",
  "Lenz's Law — the induced EMF opposes the change": "",
  "It's a mathematical convention only": "",
  "EMF is always negative": "",
  "Flux is always negative": "",
  "The negative sign represents Lenz's Law — the induced EMF opposes the change in flux, ensuring energy conservation.": "",
  "What is the SI unit of magnetic flux?": "",
  "Tesla (T)": "",
  "Weber (Wb)": "",
  "Henry (H)": "",
  "Volt (V)": "",
  "The SI unit of magnetic flux is the Weber (Wb). 1 Wb = 1 T·m².": "",
  "Name three ways to induce an EMF in a loop.": "",
  "Change the battery voltage, add resistors, or add capacitors": "",
  "Change B, change area A, or change the angle θ between B and A": "",
  "Increase temperature, add more wire, or use a stronger insulator": "",
  "Use a bigger loop, use thicker wire, or change the wire material": "",
  "EMF can be induced by changing any factor in Φ = BA cos θ: changing the magnetic field B, the area A, or the angle θ.": "",
  "What does a transformer do?": "",
  "It stores electrical energy in a magnetic field for later use": "",
  "It converts DC voltage to AC voltage for household circuits": "",
  "It changes AC voltage levels using electromagnetic induction": "",
  "It generates electricity from mechanical rotation of a coil": "",
  "A transformer uses electromagnetic induction to change AC voltage levels. V₂/V₁ = N₂/N₁, where N is the number of turns.": "",
  "What is 'electromagnetic induction'?": "",
  "The process of generating an EMF by changing the magnetic flux through a circuit": "",
  "The process of creating a magnetic field by passing current through a straight wire": "",
  "The process of charging a capacitor by connecting it to a battery in a circuit": "",
  "The process of converting thermal energy into electrical energy using thermocouples": "",
  "Electromagnetic induction is the generation of an EMF (and current in a closed circuit) by a changing magnetic flux, as described by Faraday's Law.": "",
  "What is 'magnetic flux' in simple terms?": "",
  "The total amount of magnetic field passing through a given surface area": "",
  "The force exerted on a moving charge by a magnetic field at a point": "",
  "The speed at which magnetic field lines travel through empty space": "",
  "The number of turns of wire in a solenoid or electromagnetic coil": "",
  "Magnetic flux is the total magnetic field passing through an area: Φ = BA cos θ. It depends on field strength, area size, and the angle between them.": "",
  "What is an 'induced EMF'?": "",
  "A voltage created by a battery through chemical reactions inside the cell": "",
  "A voltage generated by a changing magnetic flux through a loop of wire": "",
  "A voltage measured across a resistor when steady current flows through it": "",
  "A voltage caused by static charge buildup on an insulated surface only": "",
  "An induced EMF is a voltage generated by a changing magnetic flux through a conducting loop. It drives current if the loop forms a complete circuit.": "",
  "What is 'Lenz's Law' in simple terms?": "",
  "The induced current always flows in the direction that produces the most heat": "",
  "The induced current flows in a direction that opposes the change causing it": "",
  "The induced current always flows clockwise when viewed from above the loop": "",
  "The induced current is proportional to the total magnetic flux in the loop": "",
  "Lenz's Law states that the induced current creates its own magnetic field that opposes the change in flux that produced it. This is a consequence of energy conservation.": "",
  "What is a 'generator' in physics?": "",
  "A device that converts electrical energy into mechanical rotational energy": "",
  "A device that converts mechanical energy into electrical energy via induction": "",
  "A device that stores electrical energy in chemical form inside a battery": "",
  "A device that increases voltage using two coils and a shared iron core": "",
  "A generator converts mechanical energy (rotation) into electrical energy by rotating a coil in a magnetic field, inducing an EMF according to Faraday's Law.": "",
  "What is a 'transformer' in electrical engineering?": "",
  "A device that changes DC voltage to AC voltage for power transmission": "",
  "A device that changes AC voltage levels using two coils and mutual induction": "",
  "A device that stores large amounts of charge for rapid discharge in circuits": "",
  "A device that converts mechanical rotation into alternating electrical current": "",
  "A transformer uses two coils (primary and secondary) wound on a shared iron core. The changing current in the primary induces an EMF in the secondary, allowing voltage to be stepped up or down.": "",
  "What does 'eddy current' mean?": "",
  "Circular induced currents in a bulk conductor caused by changing magnetic flux": "",
  "The alternating current that flows through the primary coil of a transformer": "",
  "The direct current produced by a battery in a simple DC circuit loop": "",
  "The current that flows through a superconducting wire with zero resistance": "",
  "Eddy currents are loops of electric current induced in a bulk conductor by a changing magnetic flux. They create their own magnetic fields that oppose the change (Lenz's Law) and generate heat.": "",
  "What is 'mutual induction'?": "",
  "When a changing current in one coil induces an EMF in a nearby second coil": "",
  "When two coils carry the same current and produce identical magnetic fields": "",
  "When a coil induces an EMF in itself due to its own changing current flow": "",
  "When two permanent magnets repel each other when their like poles are close": "",
  "Mutual induction occurs when a changing current in one coil creates a changing flux that induces an EMF in a nearby second coil. This is the operating principle of transformers.": "",
  "What is 'self-induction'?": "",
  "When a coil's own changing current induces an EMF in itself that opposes the change": "",
  "When an external magnet induces a current in a stationary loop of conducting wire": "",
  "When two adjacent coils transfer energy between each other through flux linkage": "",
  "When a permanent magnet spontaneously generates an electric current in open air": "",
  "Self-induction occurs when a changing current in a coil produces a changing flux through the same coil, inducing an EMF (back-EMF) that opposes the current change. Inductance L measures this effect.": "",
  "What is the 'Weber' (Wb) as a unit?": "",
  "The SI unit of magnetic flux equal to one tesla times one square meter": "",
  "The SI unit of magnetic field strength measured at a point in space": "",
  "The SI unit of inductance for a coil in a changing magnetic field": "",
  "The SI unit of electromotive force generated by a power source": "",
  "The Weber (Wb) is the SI unit of magnetic flux. 1 Wb = 1 T·m². A change of 1 Wb per second through a loop induces an EMF of 1 volt.": "",
  "A student pushes a bar magnet into a coil and sees a current on an ammeter. When they stop moving the magnet (but keep it inside), the current drops to zero. Why?": "",
  "The magnet lost its magnetism while sitting inside the coil for too long": "",
  "The coil's resistance increased and blocked the current from flowing through": "",
  "The flux is no longer changing so no EMF is induced by Faraday's Law": "",
  "The ammeter broke because it was not designed for continuous current flow": "",
  "EMF = −dΦ/dt. When the magnet is stationary inside the coil, the flux through the coil is constant (not changing), so dΦ/dt = 0 and no EMF is induced.": "",
  "A student pushes a magnet into a coil and notes the current direction. When they pull it out, the current reverses. Why?": "",
  "The magnet switches its poles when pulled back out of the coil": "",
  "The flux change reverses direction so the induced EMF reverses by Lenz's Law": "",
  "The coil's winding direction reverses the current when motion changes": "",
  "Pulling the magnet out creates a different type of electromagnetic wave": "",
  "Pushing the magnet in increases flux; pulling it out decreases flux. Lenz's Law requires the induced current to oppose the change, so the current direction reverses.": "",
  "A student uses a step-down transformer with 1000 turns on the primary and 100 turns on the secondary. If the input is 120 V, what is the output?": "",
  "The output voltage is 1200 V": "",
  "The output voltage is 12 V": "",
  "The output voltage is 120 V": "",
  "The output voltage is 1.2 V": "",
  "V₂/V₁ = N₂/N₁. V₂ = 120 × (100/1000) = 12 V.": "",
  "A student wants to increase the induced EMF when moving a magnet into a coil. What can they do?": "",
  "Move the magnet more slowly into the coil to increase the time": "",
  "Move the magnet faster, use a stronger magnet, or add more coil turns": "",
  "Use a weaker magnet and fewer turns of wire in the coil design": "",
  "Keep the magnet stationary and increase the coil's electrical resistance": "",
  "EMF = −NdΦ/dt. To increase EMF: move faster (increase dΦ/dt), use a stronger magnet (increase B and Φ), or add more turns (increase N).": "",
  "A student learns that power plants use generators. What provides the mechanical energy to spin the generator?": "",
  "The electrical energy from the power grid is recycled to spin the generator": "",
  "Turbines driven by steam, water, or wind provide the rotational energy": "",
  "Permanent magnets inside the generator spin automatically without any input": "",
  "The Earth's magnetic field provides enough force to rotate the coils": "",
  "Generators need an external source of mechanical energy. In power plants, this comes from turbines driven by steam (from coal, gas, or nuclear heat), falling water (hydroelectric), or wind.": "",
  "In a lab, a student drops a magnet through a copper tube. It falls much slower than expected. Why?": "",
  "Copper is magnetic and attracts the falling magnet strongly from all sides": "",
  "Induced eddy currents in the copper create fields that oppose the magnet's motion": "",
  "Air resistance inside the narrow copper tube slows the magnet significantly": "",
  "The magnet demagnetizes when it enters the copper tube and loses its pull": "",
  "The falling magnet creates a changing flux through the copper tube walls. This induces eddy currents that, by Lenz's Law, create magnetic fields opposing the magnet's motion, dramatically slowing its fall.": "",
  "A student builds a simple AC generator by spinning a coil between two magnets. What determines the frequency of the output?": "",
  "The number of turns in the coil determines the frequency of the output": "",
  "The rotation speed of the coil determines the frequency of the output": "",
  "The strength of the magnets determines the frequency of the output": "",
  "The resistance of the external circuit determines the frequency of output": "",
  "The frequency of the AC output equals the rotation frequency of the coil. One complete rotation produces one full cycle of alternating voltage.": "",
  "A student uses a transformer to charge a phone (from 120 V wall outlet to 5 V). Is this a step-up or step-down transformer?": "",
  "Step-up, because it increases the voltage from the wall outlet": "",
  "Step-down, because it decreases the voltage from 120 V to 5 V": "",
  "Neither, because transformers cannot change voltage by that much": "",
  "Both, because it steps up first and then steps down the voltage": "",
  "Going from 120 V to 5 V is a decrease in voltage, so this is a step-down transformer. The secondary coil has fewer turns than the primary.": "",
  "A student wonders why transformers only work with AC and not DC. Why?": "",
  "DC current is too strong for the transformer coils to handle safely": "",
  "DC produces a constant flux so there is no changing flux to induce an EMF": "",
  "DC current cannot flow through the iron core of a standard transformer": "",
  "DC voltage is always lower than AC voltage in all power systems everywhere": "",
  "Transformers require changing magnetic flux to induce an EMF in the secondary coil. DC produces a constant current and constant flux, so dΦ/dt = 0 and no voltage is induced.": "",
  "A student reads that electromagnetic braking is used in some trains. How does it work?": "",
  "Permanent magnets physically grip the rails to slow down the train": "",
  "Induced eddy currents in metal rails create opposing forces that slow the train": "",
  "An electric motor runs in reverse to absorb the train's kinetic energy": "",
  "Electromagnets attract the train toward the station platform to stop it": "",
  "Electromagnetic brakes use magnets near metal rails or discs. The train's motion creates changing flux in the metal, inducing eddy currents. By Lenz's Law, these currents oppose the motion, providing a braking force without physical contact.": ""
